<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=447372</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=quirtevans>QuirtEvans</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:blue;'>Tavern Regular</span></span><br>  Posts: 223<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(9/6/03 6:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3528.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Employment Law</span><hr size=1> A few thoughts:<br>
<br>
Employment law is mostly, not totally but mostly, a matter of state law.  Different states handle it differently.<br>
<br>
&quot;At will&quot; employment means that you can fire someone for any reason at all, or for no reason.  It generally does not mean that you can fire someone for a bad reason (because of their sex, or their race, for example).<br>
<br>
In addition, in many states, you cannot fire someone, even in an &quot;at will&quot; employment arrangement, if the reason for the firing would contravene public policy.<br>
<br>
A final point is the issue of what is generally called &quot;jury nullification&quot;.  Basically, if a defendant's actions shock the jury, the jury may decide to ignore the law and the judge's instructions and punish the defendant.  The judge does have the authority to set aside a jury verdict if that happens, which is called JNOV, or judgment notwithstanding the verdict.  A judge may also decide the cast on the law before it goes to the jury (juries are triers of fact, not triers of law).<br>
<br>
Bottom line, find a good Texas employment law litigator, talk to him or her, and find out whether there is a case here or not.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=meanntemptation>Meann Temptation</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:blue;'>Tavern Regular</span></span><br>  Posts: 419<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(9/6/03 6:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3528.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Texas Law for Uninsured Drivers</span><hr size=1> Texas has to be about the worst state in Union when it comes to Motor Vehicals both with state of disrepair of allowable (or passable) state inspection and thier we dont give a shit attitude about people who drive with no insurance.<br>
